Steps to Reproduce:

Support [optional chaining](https://github.com/tc39/proposal-optional-chaining) syntax in `javascript`/`javascriptreact` languages.

Seems like VS Code parses `?` as a ternary operator and expects `:` symbol further.

Screenshots:
[Broken syntax](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2690794/30707451-31af05c4-9f04-11e7-9b4f-12e6ff3ad2f8.png)
[Works as it should](https://i.imgur.com/9DgHStJ.png)

Code: 
```js
const a = {
  b: {
    c: {
      d: {
        e: 1,
        g: [1, 2, 3],
      },
    },
    f: null,
  },
};

const brokenSyntaxHighlighting = () => {
  const array = a?.b?.c?.d?.g;

  /**
   * No TypeEror, but syntax highlighting is broken
   */
  const test = a?.b?.f?.f;

  for (let i = 0; i < array.length; i++) {
    console.log(array[i]);
  }
};

brokenSyntaxHighlighting();
```

<!-- Launch with `code --disable-extensions` to check. -->
Reproduces without extensions: Yes
